technical_knowledge.q10_postman_review:
It only checks status 200 — a lot of bugs return 200 with an error inside the body. If the API returns:
json{ "success": false, "message": "Invalid credentials" }
This test passes. That's a real bug that gets missed.
Also no validation that token actually exists before setting it — if json.token is undefined, the environment variable gets set to undefined silently and every test after this breaks in a confusing way.

Better version:
javascriptpm.test("Login returns 200", function () {
    pm.response.to.have.status(200);
});

pm.test("Response has token", function () {
    var json = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(json.token).to.be.a('string').and.not.empty;
    pm.environment.set("token", json.token);
});

pm.test("Success flag is true", function () {
    var json = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(json.success).to.be.true;
});

pm.test("Response time under 500ms", function () {
    pm.expect(pm.response.responseTime).to.be.below(500);
});

technical_knowledge.q11_selenium_review:
1. Thread.sleep — hardcoded waits are the main reason Selenium tests are flaky. 3 seconds might be too long on a fast machine and too short on a slow CI runner.
2. XPath like //*[@id='root']/div/form/div[1]/input — this breaks if anyone changes the HTML structure even slightly. A dev adds a wrapper div, test fails for no real reason.
3. getPageSource().contains("Dashboard") — checks raw HTML, not what the user actually sees. The word "Dashboard" could be in a hidden element, a comment, or a script tag and the test still passes.

Fixed version:
javadriver.get("https://admin.example.com/login");

WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));

WebElement email = wait.until(
    ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("email"))
);
email.sendKeys("user@x.com");

driver.findElement(By.id("password")).sendKeys("secret");
driver.findElement(By.cssSelector("button[type='submit']")).click();

wait.until(
    ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("dashboard-header"))
);

Assert.assertTrue(
    driver.findElement(By.id("dashboard-header")).isDisplayed()
);
